---
import DisplayLayout from "../../layouts/DisplayLayout.astro";
---

<DisplayLayout
    title="Home"
    description="Wireless Wonder — Vintage Radio Repair & Restoration"
    headerMode="demo"
>
    <!-- hero -->
    <section class="hero">
        <h1>Bringing Dead Radios Back to Life</h1>
        <p class="lead">
            We restore, repair, and preserve vintage radios from the 1920s
            through the 1970s. Every set that leaves our bench plays the way its
            maker intended.
        </p>
        <div class="hero-actions">
            <a href="/demo/contact" class="button-primary">Book a Repair</a>
            <a href="/demo/article" class="button-ghost">Read the Guides</a>
        </div>
    </section>

    <hr />

    <!-- intro -->
    <section class="intro">
        <h2>Why Wireless Wonder?</h2>
        <p>
            Since 1987, we have been the <strong>go-to workshop</strong> for collectors,
            hobbyists, and museums across the country. Our approach is simple — <em
                >restore to original specification wherever possible</em
            >, and document everything we touch.
        </p>
        <p>
            We work on <mark>all major manufacturers</mark> including Zenith, Philco,
            RCA, Emerson, and Motorola. If it has valves, we can fix it.
        </p>
    </section>

    <hr />

    <!-- services -->
    <section class="services">
        <h2>What We Do</h2>

        <h3>Full Restoration</h3>
        <p>
            A complete restoration covers every system in the set. We recap the
            power supply, align the tuner, replace worn components, and refinish
            the cabinet where needed. The result is a radio that looks and
            sounds as it did when new.
        </p>

        <h3>Bench Repair</h3>
        <p>
            Not every set needs a full restoration. Sometimes a single failed
            component — a cracked resistor, a shorted capacitor, a broken dial
            cord — is all that stands between silence and music. We diagnose and
            fix the fault, nothing more.
        </p>

        <h3>Alignment &amp; Calibration</h3>
        <p>
            Tuners drift over decades. A proper alignment restores sensitivity
            and selectivity to factory specification. We use <abbr
                title="Signal Generator">SG</abbr
            > and <abbr title="Vacuum Tube Voltmeter">VTVM</abbr> equipment of the
            period wherever authenticity matters.
        </p>

        <h3>Cabinet Work</h3>
        <p>
            Bakelite cracks, veneer lifts, and lacquer crazes with age. We
            repair cabinets using period-appropriate materials and techniques.
            We <del>use modern lacquers as a shortcut</del> always match the original
            finish specification.
        </p>
    </section>

    <hr />

    <!-- facts -->
    <section class="facts">
        <h2>By the Numbers</h2>
        <dl>
            <dt>Years in business</dt>
            <dd>37</dd>
            <dt>Sets restored</dt>
            <dd>Over 4,200</dd>
            <dt>Manufacturers covered</dt>
            <dd>68 and counting</dd>
            <dt>Turnaround time</dt>
            <dd>4 to 8 weeks depending on parts availability</dd>
        </dl>
    </section>

    <hr />

    <!-- testimonial -->
    <section class="testimonial">
        <h2>From Our Customers</h2>
        <blockquote>
            <p>
                I brought in my grandfather's 1939 Zenith console expecting bad
                news. It left the bench playing better than I have ever heard
                it. The attention to detail is extraordinary.
            </p>
            <cite>— Margaret T., Edinburgh</cite>
        </blockquote>

        <blockquote>
            <p>
                The only workshop I trust with my collection. They have restored
                eleven sets for me over the years and every single one has been <em
                    >perfect</em
                >.
            </p>
            <cite>— Robert K., Bristol</cite>
        </blockquote>
    </section>

    <hr />

    <!-- parts note -->
    <section class="parts-note">
        <h2>A Note on Parts</h2>
        <p>
            Original components are always preferred. When a period part cannot
            be sourced, we use the closest modern equivalent and document the
            substitution. We never fit a component rated below the original
            specification.
        </p>
        <p>
            Common substitutions are noted in our <a href="/demo/article"
                >repair guides</a
            >. If you have questions about a specific set, <a
                href="/demo/contact">get in touch</a
            >.
        </p>

        <h3>What We Stock</h3>
        <ul>
            <li>Electrolytic and paper capacitors, all common values</li>
            <li>Carbon composition resistors, 1920s through 1960s values</li>
            <li>Receiving valves — over 400 types in stock</li>
            <li>Dial lamps, dial cords, and pointer assemblies</li>
            <li>Speaker field coil and voice coil repair materials</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>What We Source</h3>
        <ol>
            <li>Unusual output transformers and power transformers</li>
            <li>Pre-war IF transformers to original specification</li>
            <li>Reproduction dial glass and escutcheons</li>
            <li>Period-correct knobs and hardware</li>
        </ol>
    </section>

    <hr />

    <!-- small print -->
    <section class="small-print">
        <h2>Estimates &amp; Liability</h2>
        <p>
            All work is quoted before we begin. We will not proceed without
            written approval. Sets are held for collection for <time
                datetime="P90D">90 days</time
            > after completion.
        </p>
        <small
            >Wireless Wonder accepts no liability for sets damaged in transit.
            We recommend specialist courier services for valuable pieces. Full
            terms available on request.</small
        >
    </section>
</DisplayLayout>

<style lang="scss">
    @use "mixins" as *;

    .hero {
        padding-block: var(--space-7);
        padding-inline: var(--space-6);
        text-align: center;
        background-color: var(--color-surface);

        h1 {
            max-width: 20ch;
            margin-inline: auto;
        }
    }

    .lead {
        font-size: var(--text-lg);
        color: var(--color-text-muted);
        max-width: 60ch;
        margin-inline: auto;
    }

    .hero-actions {
        display: flex;
        gap: var(--space-4);
        justify-content: center;
        flex-wrap: wrap;
        margin-block-start: var(--space-5);
    }

    .button-primary {
        @include box-button;
        @include radius-button;
        @include focus-ring;
        background-color: var(--color-interactive);
        color: var(--color-neutral-50);
        text-decoration: none;
        font-weight: var(--font-weight-bold);

        &:hover {
            background-color: var(--color-interactive-hover);
        }
    }

    .button-ghost {
        @include box-button;
        @include radius-button;
        @include focus-ring;
        @include border;
        color: var(--color-text);
        text-decoration: none;

        &:hover {
            background-color: var(--color-surface-raised);
        }
    }

    section {
        max-width: 72ch;
        margin-inline: auto;
        padding-block: var(--space-6);
        padding-inline: var(--space-5);
    }

    .small-print {
        color: var(--color-text-muted);
    }
</style>
